segments.text: I wasn't taking ROTC at the time.
All right.
Incidentally, when I finished A&M, I volunteered.
I went to OCS, the Army, and my training as the ROTC helped me to get into OCS.
So your A&M preparation...
helped me to get into OCS.
Now you graduated when?
Did you go to commencement?
I don't really remember.
Things like that were not... You don't remember who the speaker was?
No.
Do you remember when you got that ring?
No.
Well, I remember when I got this one, I lost the first one in New Guinea.
Oh, did you?
I was swimming in New Guinea, and it fell off in the Indian Ocean.
Oh, my.
And then I got this one while I was overseas.
I bought another one.
And incidentally, this ring only cost maybe $30.
Do you remember what the first one cost?
It wasn't over $30.

wasn't much 25 30 dollars as i remember what or maybe do you have any other ring stories you lost one in the indian ocean uh what about some others about somebody spotted your ring or something like that now that hasn't been found no but is was there times when somebody noticed your ring on your yes i took up tickets at the
football games for thirty-some odd years.
I've seen a lot of the spirit change there.
Arkansas, I remember gung-ho they'd come in, and they were always a good crowd.
The Texas crowd always came in when I was working on the gates, dressed up pretty real good.

and even up until a few years back and even today I could go to the baseball game and you'd be surprised at the number of young Aggies, girls and all, will show you this old worn out ring and recognize it and introduce themselves or ask me what class I'm in and was in.
And it's surprising how
so many have really, over the years, these young people, recognized that ring.
In OCS and later, what was it that you learned here that helped you?
What was there about A&M that made a difference?
Well, respect of authority, that's one thing.
And understanding the principles of drilling and commands.
And respecting authority is one of the biggest things I think I learned.
And to do what you're told to do.
What is Aggie spirit?
Well, I saw that one time.
I was on a boat going up to Tokyo, Yokohama.
We had left the Philippines, and I was with a young man, a fellow, and he had graduated from some military school in Virginia, I believe, somewhere.
And he had gone into a class.
See, at that time then they were bringing in Aggies from ROTC that had a commission, but they were making them go into another, what, refresher course.
And if they didn't pass that refresher course, they didn't keep them on duty.
And he had learned every Aggie yell, even though he was with a bunch of Aggies.
He had learned every Aggie yell and learned that.
However, he did say this, that they had one or two Aggies that were a little bit hanging back, and he said they could have really carried them through, but they didn't do it.
He said he was somewhat surprised that they let them drop out.
I remember him saying that.
I remember over in New Guinea, though, there was an old colonel in charge of the Air Force.
We had a, we sent a plane down to Australia and we got some
a keg of beer and some chickens.
And we had the Aggie, what do they call it, reunion?
Mustard.
Mustard.
We had that in New Guinea there one time.
And there were a bunch of Aggies there in New Guinea at the time.
Was that a meaningful experience?
Well, it was.
This old colonel that I knew,
And we got a bunch of Aggies there together and had a monster there.
And he'd let us send a plane down to, I wasn't in, I was attached to that unit.
I wasn't in the Air Force.
And send a plane down to Australia and get a keg of beer.
some barbecued chickens now, that was a treat.
And we got a bunch of aggies and had a nice muster.
Do you remember going to muster when you were a student?
No, I don't.
I haven't found many people that remember muster before World War II.
The only one I actually remember was when I was in New Guinea.
What are the qualities of being an aggie?
What's special about an aggie?
Well, as I remember there, we were with each other and respected each other and trusted each other and felt like that our other Aggie
would be there to help us or whatnot.
And most of us at that time, you might say, understood and respected where these others came from, that they were poor boys, too.
See, any one
I think that was a feeling that had maybe perhaps is different from today.
We all knew the backgrounds of these people, what a lot of them did to be able to come to A&M, which drew us very well together.
And there wasn't anybody, you might say, football players or anybody that was any more than somebody else.
And it didn't matter where you came from or who your father was?
That's right.
And of course we didn't have any politics.
That wasn't the internet to any of us.
What have we left out that we should have covered?
Well, I don't know.
I can't
Well, let's see.
When I finished A&M, until I got this job in New Orleans, I went down to Houston to try to see about getting a job.
Jobs were very hard to get, very hard.
There was a green company down there, Archer I'm thinking,
I would have been able to get a job there, but they called me in and said, we don't care whether you graduated from college or not.
And that was the general attitude.
They said, no, but we'll let you get a job.
We'll put you on the dock out here.
load and unload and feed and drain, and we'll see how you turn out.
Also, I had a chance, possibly, of getting a job with a concrete company in Houston as a clerk or something like that.
And I almost had another chance of getting a job, I believe it was with Guff Refining Company in the accounting department, since I had some accounting at A&M.
But that wasn't very promising, and I ended up getting this job in New Orleans with American Cotton Co-op as a cotton class.
I was what they called a squidge, as I remember.
I had to work as a squidge or an apprentice until later.
But I worked there in the classroom rooms there in New Orleans.
Made seventy-five dollars a month and lived there, and I live down in New Orleans now for ten thousand.
I lost my job when they put the twelve-cent loan on.
Let's see, I'm near the end of the questions.
I can think I've got three or four.
Let's make believe that someone comes up and gives you a check for a million dollars today and there is one restriction on that check.
You must pass it on to Texas A&M but you get to decide what the money would be used for.
In other words, if you could make a big contribution to A&M, what would you want it to do?
I believe mostly it would be for scholarship, not research.
Scholarships for whom?
What kind of students?
Well, I try to make it for students who
Not financially, but go to A&M.
How would you select the most deserving ones?
I haven't given that a whole lot of thought.
Could they major in anything?
Would it matter?
No, it wouldn't matter because I found that
The more you continue to learn throughout life, and regardless of what you take, in other words, it's a good idea to get an overall thing done.
All right, next to the last question.
What did it mean to your life that you went to Texas A&M?
Well, I've always been proud of the college and that I could, I think it's helped me a whole lot.
It helped me.
I haven't been real successful in making a whole lot of money.
However, I'm financially stable now.
I think I learned something way back there when I went to A&M that I wouldn't have gotten at some other school.
What feelings do you have in your heart for A&M today?
Well, today I think, for instance, I went to the baseball game the other day.
I had
hard season for them.
And I just love A&M, particularly now the baseball.
I feel fortunate that I can go to baseball games at A&M, in preference to pro games down in Houston or Dallas, and I
I like to see it because I think that those boys are playing there for the love of A&M.
A lot of them know they're not going to be professionals, but they're playing and it'll help them later in life.
I don't care to see some of the research that's going on in A&M now.
And I don't like particularly sometimes they have some professors I've heard that some of the students don't understand.
Sometimes, of course, the classes are larger, but we've got to accept that.
I can't say I could carry the love for Antium now as I did back there when it was a college.
I feel fortunate, and I wouldn't mind going through it again.
I wouldn't change it.
I'm glad.
I'm happy about it.

all right now that's the end of the real interview but I'm worried that we didn't get that first part I'm worried about our machine so let's go back and you again please summarize growing up where you were born your family and that that first five minutes or so that you did this morning okay where were you born what'd your family do where'd they come from that sort of thing where'd y'all live
Well, I was born somewhere around College Station on September 22, 1913.
My mother was the daughter of W.C. Boyd, lived at College Station, and he lived, he built a home there located where the campus theater is now.
I was born, I didn't, there was no birth certificate when I was born.
Later in my life, when I went in the Army, my mother had to fix a birth certificate up for me.
I moved to San Antonio when I was very young, and then moved back to College Station when I was about eight years old, and my mother had a house across from my grandfather
which is, my grandfather lived, as I say, in the home he built while the campus here is.
And I went to Consolidated School, the old band hall on the campus.
I had to walk from my house over across the campus, and I remember going across the drill field all of the
That's where I graduated from in 1931.
And how many in your class?
You think 15?
It might have been 15, possibly 20 at the most, I think.
And campus and country?
What's that?
Both.
Consolidated school was composed of what we called the campus kids and the off-campus kids.
I was an off-campus kid.
And the country kids.
The country kids came from around maybe Welborn and out at Rock Prairie.
And the buses carried those kids back and forth.
The rest of us had to walk school.
which was no problem.
And some of the key teachers at the school that you remember?
I remember we had a principal came named Gross.
He took several of us one time over to Huntsville.
I don't know what for.
Also, I had a teacher,
Mrs. Burgess, which was the wife of Herschel Burgess, and Mrs. Burgess was the daughter of Dr. T.O.
Walton, and she taught English, I think it was, or some courses there at Consolidated School.
I liked her very much, of course.
Also, there was a Mrs. Dokes at Consolidated School, and she was very well liked.
Matter of fact, we liked all of our teachers really.
There was no teacher that I knew of that we didn't like.
I told you about A&M about Mr. Snuggs.
You got that, haven't you?
I think we got it.
I believe now we're caught up.
